DAILY ASIA-PAC OPENING NEWS
content:
ASIA-PAC

The next round of US/China trade talks were reportedly "in flux" and talks are said to have stalled. (CNBC)

China Foreign Minister Wang Yi said recent words and actions by US have harmed interests of China and its enterprises, while he added that China oppose these actions and warned the US to not go too far. Wang added that the trade dispute must be solved through negotiation on an equal footing and hopes both sides will avoid escalating tensions. (Newswires)

China's Global Times said China will certainly retaliate to the barbaric suppression of Huawei and suggested that this is the unanimous attitude of officials and the Chinese people. (Twitter)

Australia’s ruling Coalition led by PM Morrison is set to remain in power for a 3rd consecutive term following the Federal election on Saturday with the incumbents having at least 75 seats vs. 67 seats for Labor, with some seats still to be declared. (News.com.au)

 

UK/EU

UK PM May said the Brexit withdrawal agreement bill will have an improved package of measures according to an Op Ed, however there were separate reports that her new offer to UK lawmakers contains nothing new on customs arrangement and retains the Northern Irish backstop. (Sunday Times/Telegraph)

UK PM May's spokesperson said that it is clear that we were never going to get an agreement with the opposition on Brexit and that they are considering the next steps on indicative votes. (Newswires)

UK Labour leader Corbyn said on Friday that Brexit talks "have gone as far as they can" and that he will oppose PM May's Brexit deal. There were also comments from Labor spokesperson Starmer that the government must include provision for public vote in the withdrawal agreement bill to break impasse with Labour, while party sources suggested that the indicative vote process that been leaked is "dead on arrival" and that they will not cooperate with the government. (Newswires).

ECB’s Knot commented that Eurozone inflation is not where the central bank wants it. (Newswires)

Fitch affirmed Ireland at 'A+'; Outlook Stable. (Newswires) 

 

COMMODITIES

OPEC and allies are said to have stepped nearer to maintaining production targets through the end of the year, while officials were also said to be examining a handful of scenarios including some of which involve easing production curbs. (WSJ)

Saudi Energy Minister Al Falih stated that there is consensus to drive down inventories gently and Saudi Arabia sees no need to boost production quickly now with oil at around USD 70/bbl, while Kuwait Oil Minister said OPEC+ countries’ compliance to oil output cuts is very large and assured Kuwait’s continued cooperation as well as commitment to output agreement to create balance in the market. (Newswires)

Saudi Arabia and Russia are said to be discussing two main scenarios for a meeting of OPEC/Non-OPEC in June and both frameworks propose raising crude output from the second half of 2019, two sources familiar with the matter said. (Newswires)

OPEC+ cut compliance was about 150% in April according to delegates, while there were also reports that Iranian crude exports have fallen to 500k BPD or lower since the imposition of new tariffs. (Newswires)

 

GEOPOLITICS

US President Trump stated it would be the official end of Iran if the country wants to fight, while he warned Iran to never threaten the US again. (Twitter)

US State Department confirmed a rocket was launched into the Green Zone near the US embassy in Baghdad, Iraq. (Newswires) 

 

US

White House are reportedly set to announce an auto tariff delay of up to six months in which President Trump will direct USTR Lighthizer to lead negotiations and update him within 180 days before deciding on further actions/tariffs, according to sources. In related news, President Trump said EU is treating the US worse than the US is treating the EU and suggested the US does love Europe but have to be careful, while EU Trade Commissioner Malmstrom said EU noted the US decision to postpone auto tariffs but completely reject that their car exports are a national security threat and commented that EU is prepared to negotiate a "limited" trade deal with the US. (Newswires)

A deal was reportedly reached for US to lift tariffs on steel & aluminium from Canada and Mexico according to reports on Friday, while a Mexican Official said Mexico and Canada will lift retaliatory tariffs on US products once the US announces a deal on lifting tariffs on metal import. (Washington Post)

 

MARKET RECAP

Johnson & Johnson (JNJ) opened lower, under pressure after the emergence of news that the drug maker was under FBI investigation over corruption concerns in Brazil. Microsoft (MSFT) was under pressure despite the news that the technology co and Sony (SNE), have struck a deal to form a partnership on video game streaming, where Sony will use Microsoft’s Azure cloud service for its own PlayStation streaming service. Tesla (TSLA) shares were under pressure premarket after CEO Musk announced new cost-cutting efforts following losses in the most recent quarter and news also emerged that the electric automaker will also scale back its plans for autopilot in Europe in wake of regulatory changes. Applied Materials (AMAT) caught a bid after the chipmaker reported strong earnings, beating on both top and bottom lines whilst also raising guidance. Baidu (BIDU) sunk after the technology co lowered its Q3 profit guidance and missed bottom line earning expectations. Nvidia (NVDA) moved higher after the chipmaker reported earnings that beat on top and bottom lines, whilst also rising guidance for Q2, despite the CFO citing difficult outlook going forward. Deere & Co (DE) shares sunk after the manufacturer reported a miss on profit expectations and revised FY19 revenue guidance lower, seeing further downside as the co announced that H2 shipments could be down “in the 20% range”. Hewlett Packard Enterprise (HPE) moved higher after the technology maker confirmed its plans to purchase Cray Inc (CRAY), as the firm seeks to become more competitive in the supercomputer space. Under Armour (UA, UAA) jumped higher after receiving an upgrade from JPM, the investment group citing confidence in the brands direction. Starbucks (SBUX) moved higher with the market, unaffected by the prospect of potential future rival Luckin’ Coffee Inc (LK) first day as a publicly traded company. Wynn (WYNN) and MGM Resorts (MGM) saw some positive ticks after reports emerged that the two were in talks for a potential sale of their Encore Boston Harbour, but ultimately finished lower. S&P 500 -0.6% at 2859, NASDAQ-100 -1% at 7504, Dow Jones -0.4% at 25763.

Treasury yields were lower, and the curve flattened a touch on Friday, after hawkish trade rhetoric out of China. Decent University of Michigan data brought the complex off highs in the US afternoon, and there was further downside on reports that the US would drop metals tariffs on Canadian and Mexican steel and aluminium. US T-Note futures settled 2 ticks higher at 124-15+.
